I";<p>After reading <a href="http://sts10.github.io/blog/2015/09/14/bell-labs-the-idea-factory/">a history of Bell Labs</a>, I took a slight detour in my reading list. First, I read about half of <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Information-Theory-Introduction-James-Stone/dp/0956372856/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1442798583&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=information+theory+tutorial">an introduction to information theory</a>, then sort of bailed when I got to calculating the information entropy of continuous variables and jumped to a lighter history of cryptography called <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Code-Book-Science-Secrecy-Cryptography/dp/0385495323/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1442798113&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=code+book">The Code Book: The Science of Secrecy from Ancient Egypt to Quantum Cryptography</a> by Simon Singh.</p>
